  "prompt": "Why do airplanes use two-pronged headphones?",
  "response": "Airplanes commonly use two-pronged headphones for several reasons:\n\n1. **Dual Audio Channels**: The two-pronged design typically provides separate connections for the left and right audio channels, resulting in better sound quality and stereo sound. This separation helps in delivering a more immersive audio experience for passengers.\n\n2. **Monitored Systems**: In many aircraft, the two-prong connectors are designed to work with the aircraft's audio systems, allowing passengers to access in-flight entertainment through a standardized connection that can be easily integrated into the cabin's audio system.\n\n3. **Compatibility**: The two-pronged headphone design is a standard that has been widely adopted in the aviation industry, making it easy for airlines to source compatible equipment for their in-flight services. Many in-flight entertainment systems are designed to work with this type of connector.\n\n4. **Durability**: Aircraft environments require durable and reliable equipment. The two-pronged connector design can be more robust than standard single-jack headphones, ensuring that it withstands the wear and tear associated with frequent use.\n\n5. **Preventing Loss**: Some airlines provide headsets that use this two-pronged connector specifically to reduce the likelihood of passengers losing or misplacing them, as they are often only available during the flight.\n\nIn summary, the use of two-pronged headphones in airplanes enhances audio quality, ensures compatibility with in-flight systems, provides durability, and serves practical purposes for airlines and passengers alike.",
